<title>Fat Chance</title>
<course_type>Lecture</course_type>
<course_level code="P">Primarily for Undergraduates</course_level>
<credit code="1">Half course</credit>
<meeting_text>M., W., F., at 11, and a weekly section to be arranged.</meeting_text>
<faculty_text>Joseph D. Harris (Mathematics) and Benedict H. Gross (Mathematics)</faculty_text>
<description>This course has three objectives: to learn to calculate probabilities precisely, when we can; to learn how to estimate them, when we can't; and to say exactly what we can and can't infer from these calculations. The course is not mathematically demanding--we assume no mathematical background beyond high-school algebra--but the goal is serious: given that we're asked every day to make consequential decisions on the basis of incomplete knowledge, an understanding of basic probability is an essential tool for life.</description>
